{0 UTF-16 position encoding}

Handle non-ASCII text correctly by converting between UTF-16 offsets
(LSP wire format) and byte offsets (internal representation).

{1 Background}

The LSP specification defines [Position.character] as a UTF-16 code-unit
offset within the line.  The current implementation treats [character] as
a byte offset, which is correct only for ASCII content.  Any document
containing multi-byte UTF-8 characters (e.g. CJK, emoji, accented
letters) will produce incorrect cursor positions.

{1 Scope}

This is a cross-cutting concern that affects every feature that converts
an LSP position to an internal byte offset or vice versa:

{ul
  {- {!page-"feature-go-to-definition"}: cursor-to-link matching}
  {- {!page-"feature-hover"}: cursor-to-link matching}
  {- {!page-"feature-find-references"}: result ranges}
  {- {!page-"feature-diagnostics"}: diagnostic ranges}
}

{1 Conversion}

{2 LSP position → byte offset}

Given a 0-based [(line, character)] pair where [character] is a UTF-16
code-unit count:

{ol
  {- Locate the start of the target [line] in the UTF-8 content (byte
     scan for the [line]-th newline, as today).}
  {- Walk the line byte-by-byte, decoding UTF-8 sequences.  For each
     code point, add its UTF-16 length (1 unit for BMP, 2 units for
     supplementary) to a running UTF-16 counter.  Stop when the
     counter reaches [character].}
  {- The current byte position is the result.}
}

{2 Byte offset → LSP position}

The inverse: given a byte offset, compute the 0-based line and UTF-16
character offset.

{ol
  {- Count newlines before the offset to determine [line].}
  {- From the start of that line to the offset, decode UTF-8 sequences
     and sum their UTF-16 lengths to determine [character].}
}

{1 Negotiation}

LSP 3.17 introduced [positionEncoding] capability negotiation.  The
server should advertise support for [utf-16] (mandatory baseline) and
optionally [utf-32] or [utf-8].  If the client requests [utf-8], the
conversion simplifies to a byte count (current behavior).

{t
  | Client encoding | character semantics | Conversion cost |
  |-----------------|---------------------|-----------------|
  | [utf-16]        | UTF-16 code units   | UTF-8 decode    |
  | [utf-32]        | Unicode code points | UTF-8 decode    |
  | [utf-8]         | bytes               | none (identity) |
}

{1 Implementation site}

All conversion logic lives in [lsp_util.ml], keyed on an [encoding] type
([Utf8 | Utf16 | Utf32]):

{ul
  {- {!Lsp_lib.Util.byte_offset_of_position} and
     {!Lsp_lib.Util.position_of_byte_offset} both take a
     [?encoding] parameter defaulting to [Utf16] — the mandatory
     baseline — so every existing caller becomes UTF-16-correct with no
     signature change. Both decode UTF-8 with
     [Stdlib.String.get_utf_8_uchar] and count code units per the
     negotiated encoding.}
  {- The server advertises [positionEncoding = utf-16] in its
     capabilities. Only UTF-16 is advertised today, so negotiation always
     resolves to UTF-16; the [~encoding] parameter carries the plumbing
     for offering [utf-8]/[utf-32] later.}
}

{2 Out of scope (byte column remains)}

{!Lsp_lib.Util.position_of_textloc} — used for the go-to-definition
{e target} column (see {!page-"feature-go-to-definition".target_position})
— derives its character from a [Cmarkit.Textloc] without the target
file's content, so it cannot decode UTF-8 and stays a byte column. Making
it UTF-16-correct requires go-to-definition to read the target file;
that is deferred with the same follow-up.

{1 Edge cases}

{ul
  {- {b Incomplete UTF-8 sequence at end of line}: clamp to end of
     line (same as current clamping behavior).}
  {- {b Surrogate pairs} (code points above U+FFFF): one code point
     consumes 2 UTF-16 units and 4 UTF-8 bytes.}
  {- {b ASCII-only content}: UTF-16 offsets coincide with byte
     offsets; no behavioral change.}
}
